\begin{frame}{Technical Analysis}
Technical analysis
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item Has been around for hundreds of year (Japanese rice markets)
\item Seeks to identify trends
\begin{itemize}
\item ``The trend is your friend"
\end{itemize}
\item Seeks to identify the bursting of a bubble
\item All the news, information, sentiment and positioning is in the price and the evolution of price to this point
\item Edwards and Magee, 1981, "Technical Analysis of Stock Trends"
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Identifying trends}
``The trend is your friend"
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item Evolution of sentiment
\item Bubble building 
\item Stay with trend/bubble until there is some sign that things are changing
\item Look for confirmation of signals
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Building blocks}
The standard chart to use is a high-low-close chart
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item It records the high low and close
\item If there is a
\begin{itemize}
\item higher open
\item higher high
\item higher low
\item higher close
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\pause
\begin{block}{}
The tend is intact!
\end{block}
\pause
Otherwise, there are doubts
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Support and resistance}
Highs and lows are very important: they show where buying and selling pressure was sufficient to change direction
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item At the high
\begin{itemize}
\item There was more selling than buying
\item Those willing to bet that the security was over-valued had more fire-power than those willing to bet that it was undervalued
\end{itemize}
\item At the low
\begin{itemize}
\item There was more buying than selling
 Those willing to bet that the securities was undervalued had more fire-power than those willing to bet that was overvalued
\end{itemize}
\item There was a change of direction that these points
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

